{{distinct|text=[[Bhatnagar–Gross–Krook operator|Bhatnagar–Gross–Krook]] in statistical physics, also abbreviated as BGK}}
'''Bernstein–Greene–Kruskal modes''' (a.k.a. '''BGK modes''') are nonlinear [[Electrostatic Wave|electrostatic waves]] that propagate in a unmagnetized, collisionless [[Plasma (physics)|plasma]]. They are nonlinear solutions to the [[Vlasov equation#The Vlasov–Poisson equation|Vlasov–Poisson equation]] in [[plasma physics]],<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Ng|first=C. S.|last2=Bhattacharjee|first2=A.|date=2005|title=Bernstein-Greene-Kruskal Modes in a Three-Dimensional Plasma|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=95|issue=24|pages=245004|doi=10.1103/physrevlett.95.245004|pmid=16384391|issn=0031-9007}}</ref> and are named after physicists [[Ira B. Bernstein]], [[John M. Greene]], and [[Martin David Kruskal|Martin D. Kruskal]], who solved and published the exact solution for the one-dimensional case in 1957.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bernstein|first=Ira B.|last2=Greene|first2=John M.|last3=Kruskal|first3=Martin D.|date=1957|title=Exact Nonlinear Plasma Oscillations|journal=Physical Review|volume=108|issue=3|pages=546–550|doi=10.1103/PhysRev.108.546}}</ref>
BGK modes have been studied extensively in numerical simulations for two- and three-dimensional cases,<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Demeio|first=Lucio|last2=Holloway|first2=James Paul|date=1991|title=Numerical simulations of BGK modes|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-plasma-physics/article/numerical-simulations-of-bgk-modes/87F61FAC534E81E880A2C12BCE3AA8B4|journal=Journal of Plasma Physics|language=en|volume=46|issue=1|pages=63–84|doi=10.1017/S0022377800015956|issn=1469-7807|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manfredi|first=Giovanni|last2=Bertrand|first2=Pierre|date=2000|title=Stability of Bernstein–Greene–Kruskal modes|journal=Physics of Plasmas|language=en|volume=7|issue=6|pages=2425–2431|doi=10.1063/1.874081|issn=1070-664X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Berk|first=H. L.|last2=Breizman|first2=B. N.|last3=Candy|first3=J.|last4=Pekker|first4=M.|last5=Petviashvili|first5=N. V.|date=1999|title=Spontaneous hole–clump pair creation|journal=Physics of Plasmas|language=en|volume=6|issue=8|pages=3102–3113|doi=10.1063/1.873550|issn=1070-664X}}</ref> and are believed to be produced by the [[two-stream instability]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Omura|first=Y.|last2=Matsumoto|first2=H.|last3=Miyake|first3=T.|last4=Kojima|first4=H.|date=1996|title=Electron beam instabilities as generation mechanism of electrostatic solitary waves in the magnetotail|journal=Journal of Geophysical Research: Space Physics|language=en|volume=101|issue=A2|pages=2685–2697|doi=10.1029/95ja03145|issn=0148-0227}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dieckmann|first=M. E.|last2=Eliasson|first2=B.|last3=Shukla|first3=P. K.|date=2004|title=Streaming instabilities driven by mildly relativistic proton beams in plasmas|journal=Physics of Plasmas|language=en|volume=11|issue=4|pages=1394–1401|doi=10.1063/1.1649996|issn=1070-664X}}</ref> They have been observed as electron phase space holes (electrostatic solitary structures)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Turikov|first=V. A.|date=1984|title=Electron Phase Space Holes as Localized BGK Solutions|url=http://stacks.iop.org/1402-4896/30/i=1/a=015|journal=Physica Scripta|language=en|volume=30|issue=1|pages=73-77|doi=10.1088/0031-8949/30/1/015|issn=1402-4896}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fox|first=W.|last2=Porkolab|first2=M.|last3=Egedal|first3=J.|last4=Katz|first4=N.|last5=Le|first5=A.|date=2008|title=Laboratory Observation of Electron Phase-Space Holes during Magnetic Reconnection|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=101|issue=25|pages=255003|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.101.255003|pmid=19113719}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vasko|first=I. Y.|last2=Kuzichev|first2=I. V.|last3=Agapitov|first3=O. V.|last4=Mozer|first4=F. S.|last5=Artemyev|first5=A. V.|last6=Roth|first6=I.|date=2017|title=Evolution of electron phase space holes in inhomogeneous plasmas|journal=Physics of Plasmas|language=en|volume=24|issue=6|pages=062311|doi=10.1063/1.4989717|issn=1070-664X}}</ref> and [[Double layer (plasma physics)|double layers]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Quon|first=B. H.|last2=Wong|first2=A. Y.|date=1976|title=Formation of Potential Double Layers in Plasmas|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=37|issue=21|pages=1393–1396|doi=10.1103/physrevlett.37.1393|issn=0031-9007}}</ref> in space plasmas, as well as in scattering experiments in the laboratory.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Montgomery|first=D. S.|last2=Focia|first2=R. J.|last3=Rose|first3=H. A.|last4=Russell|first4=D. A.|last5=Cobble|first5=J. A.|last6=Fernández|first6=J. C.|last7=Johnson|first7=R. P.|date=2001|title=Observation of Stimulated Electron-Acoustic-Wave Scattering|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=87|issue=15|pages=155001|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.87.155001|pmid=11580704}}</ref>
== Small-amplitude limit: Van Kampen modes == In the linear limit of BGK modes (e.g. in the small amplitude approximation), the solutions reduce to what is known as '''Van Kampen modes''',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/9852700|title=Introduction to plasma physics and controlled fusion|last=Chen|first=Francis F.|date=1984|publisher=Plenum Press|others=|year=|isbn=0306413329|edition=2nd|location=New York|pages=261-262|oclc=9852700}}</ref> named after [[Nico van Kampen]] who derived the solutions in 1955.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Van Kampen|first=N. G.|date=1955|title=On the theory of stationary waves in plasmas|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031891455930688|journal=Physica|language=en|volume=21|issue=6-10|pages=949–963|doi=10.1016/S0031-8914(55)93068-8|issn=0031-8914|via=}}</ref> The [[Phase (waves)|phase]] mixing of Van Kampen modes gives rise to [[Landau damping]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ng|first=C. S.|last2=Bhattacharjee|first2=A.|last3=Skiff|first3=F.|date=2006|title=Weakly collisional Landau damping and three-dimensional Bernstein-Greene-Kruskal modes: New results on old problems|url=https://aip.scitation.org/doi/pdf/10.1063/1.2186187|journal=Physics of Plasmas|language=en|volume=13|issue=5|pages=055903|doi=10.1063/1.2186187|issn=1070-664X|via=}}</ref>
== Quantum BGK (QBGK) modes == BGK modes have been generalized to [[quantum mechanics]], in which the solutions (called '''quantum BGK modes''') solve the quantum equivalent of the Vlasov–Poisson system known as the [[Wigner quasiprobability distribution|Wigner–Poisson system]], with periodic boundary conditions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Demeio|first=L.|date=2007|title=Quantum Corrections to Classical BGK Modes in Phase Space|journal=Transport Theory and Statistical Physics|language=en|volume=36|issue=1–3|pages=137–158|doi=10.1080/00411450701456857|issn=0041-1450}}</ref> The solutions for the QBGK modes were put forth by Lange et al. in 1996,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lange|first=Horst|last2=Toomire|first2=Bruce|last3=Zweifel|first3=P. F.|date=1996|title=Quantum BGK modes for the Wigner-poisson system|journal=Transport Theory and Statistical Physics|language=en|volume=25|issue=6|pages=713–722|doi=10.1080/00411459608222920|issn=0041-1450}}</ref> with potential applications to quantum plasmas.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Haas|first=F.|last2=Manfredi|first2=G.|last3=Feix|first3=M.|date=2000|title=Multistream model for quantum plasmas|journal=Physical Review E|volume=62|issue=2|pages=2763–2772|doi=10.1103/PhysRevE.62.2763|arxiv=cond-mat/0203405}}</ref>
