The '''Green Mountain Wind Energy Center''' was a wind [[power plant]] near [[Garrett, Pennsylvania|Garrett]], [[Somerset County, Pennsylvania]] with eight [[Nordex|Nordex 1.3 MW turbine]]s that began commercial operation in May 2000.<ref name="windpower">[http://www.pawindenergynow.org/pa/farms.html Wind farms in Pennsylvania] Pennsylvania Wind Working Group, accessed March 3, 2010.</ref> This was the first commercial [[wind farm]] constructed in Pennsylvania.<ref name="green">[http://www.greenmountainenergy.com/about/our_facilities.shtml Green Mountain Energy facilities] [[Green Mountain Energy]], accessed March 3, 2010.</ref> The wind farm had a combined total [[Intermittent power source#Terminology|nameplate capacity]] of 10.4 MW and the potential to produce about 27,000 [[megawatt-hours]] of electricity annually, enough to power 3,300 homes, assuming a 30% capacity factor.<ref name="pennfuture">[http://www.pennfuture.org/content.aspx?SectionID=192&MenuID= Wind farms in Pennsylvania] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127173127/http://pennfuture.org/content.aspx?SectionID=192&MenuID= |date=2010-11-27 }} PennFuture: Citizens for Pennsylvania's Future, accessed March 3, 2010.</ref> The wind farm was developed by National Wind Power of the UK, now part of NPower Renewables, operated by [[NextEra Energy Resources]], based in [[Florida]].<ref name="actionpa">[http://www.actionpa.org/cleanenergy/wind.html Commercial Wind Power in Pennsylvania] accessed March 3, 2010.</ref> Energy from the wind farm was purchased and sold by [[Green Mountain Energy]] based in [[Texas]],<ref name="actionpa" /> and was the first commercial wind farm for Green Mountain Energy.<ref name="green" /> In 2016 the wind farm was dismantled and replaced with new battery technology.<ref name="decommisioned">[http://www.tribdem.com/news/battery-system-replacing-some-somerset-county-windmills/article_a99caed2-ac80-11e6-8bfd-5ba1557c0ca5.html Johnstown Tribune Democrat] accessed June 1, 2017</ref>

