{{Infobox power station | name = Okhotnykovo Solar Park | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = Okhotnykovo Solar Park. | image_alt = | location_map = Crimea | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|45|14|20|N|33|35|34|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = | location = Okhotnykovo, [[Crimea]] | status = O | construction_began = March 2011 | commissioned = October 2011 | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = | operator = | solar_type = PV | ps_units_operational = 360,000 | solar_csp_heliostats = | ps_electrical_capacity = 82,65 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = 13,8% | ps_annual_generation = 100 [[GWh]] | website = | extra = }} The '''Okhotnykovo Solar Power Station''' is a [[Photovoltaic power station]] in [[Crimea]] with [[installed capacity]] of 82,65&nbsp;[[megawatt]]s (MW). {{As of|April 2012}}, it is the [[List of photovoltaic power stations|world's 6th largest]] solar plant and the second largest PV station in central and eastern Europe.<ref name=pv-tech>{{cite web |url=http://www.pv-tech.org/news/mission_accomplished_for_activ_solar_final_phase_of_ukraine_solar_plant_com |title=Mission accomplished for Activ Solar: final phase of Ukraine solar plant completed |author= |date= 30 September 2011 |work= pv-tech.org }}</ref> The power station is located at Okhotnykovo in Crimea, Ukraine and was developed by the Austrian company [[Activ Solar]]. The first and second phases of the project were commissioned in July 2011, the third and fourth in October 2011.<ref name=pv-tech/>
The park comprises 360,000&nbsp;modules, generating around 100&nbsp;[[GWh]] of electricity per year, enough to meet the needs of 20,000&nbsp;households.<ref name=pv-tech/> The larger capacity is installed in the plants in [[Perovo Solar Park|Perovo]] (Ukraine, 100&nbsp;MW), [[Sarnia Photovoltaic Power Plant|Sarnia]] Canada (97&nbsp;MW) and [[Montalto di Castro Photovoltaic Power Station|Montalto di Castro]] Italy (84.2&nbsp;MW).<ref name=pv-tech1>{{cite web |url=http://www.pv-tech.org/news/activ_solar_connects_first_phase_of_80mw_ukrainian_solar_plant_to_grid |title=Activ Solar completes first phases of 80&nbsp;MW Ukrainian solar plant |date= 30 September 2011 |work= pv-tech.org }}</ref>
The solar power plant is part of the Ukraine's National Natural Energy Project which is aiming to reduce Crimea's dependence on mainland Ukraine for energy. The State Agency of Ukraine for Energy Efficiency and Energy Conservation launched the project in 2010 in the hope of attracting investors to the reputed high solar radiation area, which reaches a capacity of 800-1450&nbsp;W/m2.<ref name=pv-tech/><ref name=pv-tech1/> {{clear}}
