[[File:Brabantia Pedal Bin Decor Bayon 1972.JPG|thumb|right|A pedal bin of 1972.]] A '''pedal bin''' is a [[Waste container|container]] with a lid operated by a [[foot pedal]]. [[Lillian Moller Gilbreth]] (an industrial engineer and efficiency expert as well as mother of twelve<ref>{{citation|title=Encyclopedia of Kitchen History|year=2004|author=Mary Ellen Snodgrass|page=423|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-57958-380-4}}</ref>) invented the pedal bin in the 1920s for the disposal of [[Food waste|kitchen waste]]. The footpedal enables the user to open the lid without touching it with their hands.
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Waste containers]] [[Category:Pedals]] {{waste-stub}}

In [[Plasma (physics)|plasma physics]], '''plasma containment''' refers to the act of maintaining a [[Plasma (physics)|plasma]] in a discrete volume. For example, a toroidal fusion reactor is a plasma containment device. [[Electromagnet]]ic interaction must often be used since plasma is ordinarily hotter than the [[Chemical decomposition|degradation]] temperature of any known material.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cap|first=Ferdinand F.|chapter=8. Plasma confinement |title=Handbook on plasma instabilities|year=1976|publisher=[[Academic Press]]|location=New York (etc.)|isbn=9780323148757|pages=131&ndash;178}}</ref>
